{"id": "xd_alc_ant_001", "question": "What are the geographical origins and teachings associated with the Central and Western Branches of alchemical traditions, and how might these be visually represented alongside cultural sites like Wat Chedi Chet Theu?", "query_type": "cross_domain_bridge", "collection_id": "4d57db47-5791-410e-aaf0-7f0d21c522d9", "secondary_collection_id": "5eeec701-511d-4f85-b8b5-6cbcd64e4467", "document_ids": ["f13a7592-03ee-4523-8417-9c63d63e147f", "56bcaf6a-f165-45c9-bcce-e0bca9580e9c"], "golden_chunk_ids": ["f13a7592-03ee-4523-8417-9c63d63e147f:69", "56bcaf6a-f165-45c9-bcce-e0bca9580e9c:201"], "reference_answer": "The Central Branch of alchemy, initiated by Li Daochun, emphasizes the concept of the 'center' and is geographically rooted, much like the Western Branch founded by Li Xiyue. Both branches share a historical connection with teachings derived from influential figures. In the realm of anthropology, cultural sites such as Wat Chedi Chet Theu could serve as visual representations of the geographical and spiritual origins of various traditions, establishing a link between physical locations and abstract teachings.", "expected_graph_sensitivity": "high", "tags": ["alchemy", "anthropology", "cultural origins", "geography", "teachings"]}
